label: [join] count overrides parts, complete overrides count
info: ## Join node - count versus complete versus parts The manual configuration of a join node has three different - and contra - configurations: - use existing parts - count number of messages - send when msg.complete (plus timeout but that overrides all three) What happens when all are configured? Turns out that count overrides parts meaning that even if all parts have been collected, no message is sent until all count number of messages have been received. When no count is sent, once all parts have been collected, a message is sent. Parts include an index and a count - total number of parts. That's what join uses to know when to send a message. Finally what happens if only five of six parts are sent and then a complete message is received? Complete overrides the count. There is a strange behaviour of count and complete, as described in the [forum](https://discourse.nodered.org/t/join-behaviour-count-v-use-parts-v-msg-complete/98573). ## Bug? This complete with count: delete parts all six message is passed through - because count set test is wrong for me since it should. It goes contra to the other version of this test which has no count set on join --> complete: delete parts only one message is passed through --> [forum question](https://discourse.nodered.org/t/join-behaviour-count-v-use-parts-v-msg-complete/98573).
